{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580369/1948123101/0059.xml":{"full_text":"v\nPage Four s\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nOfficial Publication\nI\nToledo Industrial Union Council\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nPublished Every Friday by Local No. IB\nUAW-CIO, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nMember of American Labor Press Association\nEditor\nSports Editor\nAdvertising Manager.\nHoward Seren\n..Wilbert A. Rule\nBurny Zawodny\nBoard of Trustees\nHoward Seren, Thomas Burke,\nRandolph Gray\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne year, by mail, in advance....................$1.50\nEntered at the To\u2019 1o, Ohio, post office as\nsecond class m_..er under the act of\nAug.^24, 1912\n(Reprint from CIO News)\nTh* \u2019Great Illusion*\nBig Business executives are doing\ntheir darndest to sell the public the idea\nthat swollen corporate profits really aren\u2019t\ntoo high.\nThey\u2019re having about as much luck as\nthe mahout who tried to hide his elephant\nin a pup tent.\nDespite the fact that they talk in tech\nnical terms designed to confuse the public,\nthey have been unable to hide two im\nportant facts:\n1. Corporate profits after payment of\ntaxes) for 1948 will total between $20 and\n21 billion more than five times the\naverage for 1936-\u201939 and more than double\nthose of the wartime peak year 1943.\n2. Prices which were necessary to\nbring about such enormous profits have\nrisen so high they are rapidly drying up\nthe consumer buying power needed for a\nhealthy economy.\nThe situation as it stands today pain\nfully reminds us of what was going on\nback in that period of wonderful nonsense\nwhich came just before the Big Bust of\n1929.\nJust so a little illusion won\u2019t be added\nto the Great Illusion which Big Business\nis trying to manufacture, let us point out\none thing::\nA lot of that \u201cconsumer resistence\u201d\nyou\u2019ve been reading about is merely the\ninability of people to buy what they want\nand need because they haven\u2019t the money.\nIt\u2019s interesting to note that the crowd\nwhich is trying to sell the idea that profits\naren\u2019t too high is the same one which\npeddled the equally sound proposition that\nTom Dewey was a cinch for the Presi\ndency.\nWhat those lads need is a Houdini.\nThere was a guy who could create an\nIllusion and make it stick!\nWe'va Often\nSaid\nThe Same Thing\nWe\u2019ll wager our best New Year's reso\nlution against an injunction that a lot of\nfolks (including us) were shocked by the\neditorial in the Dec. 18 issue of Business\nWeek, a McGraw-Hill magazine.\nThe editorial, entitled \u201cWhy the Taft\nHartley Act Failed,\" says in part:\n\u201cWhat was wrong with the Taft-Hart\nley Act was that it went too far. It crossed\nthe narrow line separating a law which\naims only to regulate from one which\ncould destroy.\n\u201cGiven a few million unemployed in\nAmerica, given an administration in\nWashington which was not pro-union\u2014\nand the Taft-Hartley Act conceivably\n.could destroy the labor movement.\n\u201cThese are the provisions which could'\ndo It: (1) picketing can be restrained by in\njunction (2) employers can petition for\na collective bargaining election (3) strikers\ncan be held ineligible to vote\u2014while the\nstrike replacements cast the only ballots,\nand (4) if the outcome of this is a 'no\nunion' vote, the government must certify\nand enforce it.\n\u201cAny time there is a surplus labor\npool from which an employer can hire at\nleast token strike replacements, these\nfour promts tons, linked together, presum\nably can destroy a union.\n\u201cBy going that far, the law defeated\nitself. It was more than a pendulum swing\naway from the Wagner Act...\u201d\nTo us there are two interesting things\nabout the Business Week editorial:\nThe magazine\u2019s labor editor served as\nlabor adviser to Tom Dewey during the\nrecent Presidential campaign.\nI The viewpoint expressed parallels the\nI stand taken by labor publications.\nOne'Stop Service\nfor year\noeds. Sound,\n1 protection\nauto,\nhisurtfnce\neconoml\nIn these\nlife, fire,\nrealty, accident\nealth, burglary and\nbbery, and ethers.\nFerm Bureau Mutual\nand\nAutomobile Insurance Co.\nFarm Bureau Mutual Fire\nInsurance Co.\nFarm Bureau Life\nInsurance Co.\nHome Office\u2014Columbus, Ohio\nCALL\nDICK C. ROBERTS\nKI. 2636 113SH Sylvania Ave.\nW1\nWhat\u2019s\nNew?\nBy Edward J. Duck,\nJournal Columnist\nIf ever there has been a\nneed for something to be done\nabout the cost of living that\ntime is now.\nWe can talk till doomsday,\nbut we must remember that\nactions speak louder than\nwords\u2014much louder.\nWhat to do about it, be\nsides turning out the lights and\ngoing to sleep that is the\nquestion.\nThe answer, friends, is for\nall of us to quit dreaming and\ndroning, complaining and wait\ning for something to happen.\n\u201cThe Lord Helps Those Who\nHelp Themselves!\u201d Let\u2019s give\nourselves a break, once and\nfor all, and end high prices\nthrough the use of consumer\nowned stores, manufacturing\nand processing plants!\nAs things now stand, you\nand I buy the supermarkets\nfor the big chain stores\u2014but\nunfortunately, we don\u2019t OWN\nthem. There are so many of\nus, our weekly food bills\namount to such great sums of\nmoney when totalled together,\nthat in no time at all we can\nown and operate our own\nstores, set our own prices, and\neventually achieve greater\neconomic security than we\nhave ever witnessed in Amer\nica or in the world.\nThe co-op plan is simple.\nOn a voluntary basis we each\nsubscribe to a $25 sharg. of\nClass A Common Stock.\nEnough of these and we will\nbe able to fill our warehouse\nsupermarket with shelves and\nshelves of finest quality grade\nlabeled groceries. In banding\ntogether, we can purchase in\ncarload lots, cutting down the\nunit cost. Then in having a\nstore that doesn\u2019t spend huge\nsums of money in advertising\nand fancy frills and fixtures\nwe can give the consumer real\ndollar value, making his pay\ncheck stretch farther. This is\nBETTER than an increase in\nwages, because it is not only\napti-inflationary, but it pre\nvents the boom-and-bust eco\nnomic cycles which always\nbring depressions after pros\nperous tin i.\nLike the person who says\n\u201cI\u2019ll join the union after the\nrest do, or after the majority\nof my fellow workers have\njoined.\u201d there are many who\nsay, \u201cI\u2019ll join the co-op after\nthe stores are built.\u201d\nThere would be no union\ncontract or organization today\nif everyone had waited until\neveryone else had joined.\nThere could be no co-op if\neveryone wanted to be the\nlast to join, either. The union\nis a good thing, as you know\nby your contracts, your wages\nand working conditions in the\nToledo area, and the co-op is\nlikewise a good thing, because\nit takes up where the labor\ncontract lets off. It protects\nthat hard-won dollar you\nworked for all day in the shop,\nand it protects the raise your\ncommittee and officers nego\ntiated for you.\nIt isn\u2019t as though we were\nmaking a donation when we\nbuy a $25 share of stock.\nRather, it is an investment\u2014\nan investment that pays divi\ndends in many ways. When we\nbuy quality goo.b at our co\nop store or wa...ouse super\nmarket, as it is called, we\nknow we\u2019re not being cheated\nIn any way. We would be fool\nish if we tried to cheat our\nselves, and after all, it is OUR\nstore, operated not for profit,\nbut for our own use.\nToo, we get immediate sav\nings because of the large scale\nbuying. The busier our store\nis, the lower the unit cost of\nour groceries. Then, at the end\nof the fiscal period, be it six\nmonths or a year, we get a\nnice patronage dividend check,\nbased on the undivided \u201cprof\nits\u201d up to that point.\nThe co-op is a wonderful\nthing. People who have learn\ned about it devote many, many\nhours without pay in promot\ning it, just as they have done\nso for the union during organi\nzational times. If anyone\ndoesn\u2019t understand it, it is not\ntheir fault, but it is the fault\nof those who do understand it\nand fail to spread the word.'\nThe drive is on, and we are\ngoing to spread that wr^d\nquickly and certainly dur\nthe next two months.\nIt your unit or local has not\nbeen approac1**! as yet, and\nyou would Lixi to have a\nspeaker attend your meeting\nto explain the co-op program\nin Toledo, if you will get in\ntouch with the writer or call\nMrs. Martha Gosline Smith, at\nLA. 9813, we will furnish a\nco-op speaker for your next\nmeeting. 1 iis holds for any or\nganization, union, fraternal, or\nchurch group.\nI*\u00abjr we hear from you?\nMaio have already rerr~ndrJ\nbut we want to comp de t-c\njob as swiftly as possible.\nNational CIO headquarters is now preparing a \u201cHand\nbook for Congressmen.** It will give low*down, in summarized\nform, on CIO\u2019s leislative program and the reasons behind\neach proposal.\nThus, no Congressmen will have eneuse that \u201che didn\u2019t\nknow what unions wanted.**\nFour CIO officials are going over to England in mid\nJanuary for heart-to-heart talks with Britain\u2019s powerful Trades\nUnion Congress. Subject of discussion: what course do two of\nthe world\u2019s largest democratic labor unions do in realm of\ninternational affairs.\nCIO convention authorized such conversations. It\u2019s no\nsecret, of course, that CIO leaders haven\u2019t been happy with\nway World Federation of Trade Unions has been running.\nFriction started with refusal of leaders of Communist labor\nmovements to support Marshall Plan, though WFTU\u2019s basic\naims call for support of economic recovery programs.\nBritish labor officials feel about the same way. They\u2019ll\ntalk over the problem together, plan a course of action in\nLondon for submission to their two organizations.\nWhat do you do about a social security program that Isn\u2019t\nvery social and doesn\u2019t provide security?\nCIO Economic Outlook, in current issue, suggests it be\ngiven thorough over-haul. In Addition, says CIO monthly maga\nzine, unions would do well to bring security problems into\ncollective bargaining meetinr\u2019i, In order to bring security\ntailored to special needs of w cers in each industry.\nHow badly social security benefits have lagged behind is\nevident in \u201cOutlook\u201d statement that a 50% rise in benefit\npayments isn\u2019t enough at least two or three times the present\nold age insurance payments must be made if\nenjoy real security CIO points out.\nWashington is incensed at ability of House\nUn American Activities to keep on smearing\nAmerican citizens, living and dead.\nLatest incident was Committee\u2019s release\nMundt, in raJio interview, also gave ins4\u201cht into way in\nwhich the Thomas Committee functions. He i i the material\nwas released by vote of majority of committee members present\nin Washington him_rlf, that is, and one other member.\nIncident v__ too raw evua for some of the other members of\nCongress\u2019s most irresponsible committee.\nIncidentally, months roll by and Dr. Edward Condon,\nler J\u2019ng government scientist, still hasn\u2019t had chance at public\nhe^..ng to deny loose charges that he is the \u201cweakest link\u201d\nin U. S. atomic energy secu y.\nThe charge was sprung at Condon more than a year ago\nat House UnAmerican Activities hearing. He denied it immedi\nhis conduct was revlewd by suprrtors in government\nand he was given clean bill of health\u2014everybody but the\nUnAmerican Activities Committee, which \u201chasn\u2019t had the time\u201d\nto hold ari i. Wheh!\nHEliL Axil) THERE: CIO Executive Board M' oduled to\nmeet in Washinton January 26 \u201cIt\u2019s in the Fanu.y,\u201d CIO\u2019s\n15-minute quiz show, opens up on ABC network Tuesday,\nJ*nua^L4, at 10:30 P.M^EST. It will be on every week until\ni'i^e\u00abTry ~ten 1 on y\u00b0ur local ABC station it\u2019s fun\nCIO Preski .t Fi.Jip Murray to be honored.at banquet in New\nYork January 12 by Labor and Nation magazine Senator\n*ra Vt. admits how he voted wrong in supporting\nGOP tax bill last year. Late admission of error is better than\nnone AFL has turned downCIO bid for a Joint legislative\nconference to cordinate labor\u2019s work in 81st Congress.\nUNION JOURNAL\nTo Men of Good Will\nON\nInside America\n(Written by the Staff of The CIO News)\nEvery business writer in the country is keeping his eyes\nglued on the price index. The guessing game which stopped\nabruptly on November 3 is back in full swi-\u2014 this time on\nthe question of business recession or no busu^ss recession?\nSome random facts indicate inflation is taking its toll.\nChristmas sales, throughout the country, trailed 1947 records.\nJob layoffs were announced in some industries. In week before\nChristmas, the consumer price index dropped nearly 1 point,\nthe biggest decline in months.\nWhat does it add up to? No one really knows. Some\neconomists think January may tell the story. Will prices drop\nmarkedly as merchants try to move their cTmumer products?\nWill people buy or hold back? Do the great n.uss of consumers\nhave the greenbacks to buy anything but day-to-day living\nneeds?\nAnswers to these questions may tell story of 1949*s eco\nnomic outlook.\nProfit question came up recently at Senate committee\ninvest! Hons, and Don Montgomery UAW-CIO economist\ntalked about what Mark Twain used to call \u201ctainted profits\n\u2019tain\u2019t yours and \u2019taint mine.\u2019\u2019\nCIO Legislative Department is getting set for hectic session\nof the brand new 81st Congress. Unions will press hard for\nadoption of Democratic Party platform as soon as possible.\npeople are\n_____ ______ of third-hand\nhearsay gossip about Lawrence Duggan, former State Dept,\nofficial who fell or jumped to his death from New York office\nbuilding. Duggan was considered one of best types of U.S.\npublic \u2014but UnA'irican Activities Committee gave\nnewspai s gossip\u2014tc-Umony allegedly linking Duggan\nwith the spy case.\npresentative Mundt soon to be a Senator\u2014lamely\nalibitea that he\u2019d voted to release the material in order, he said,\nto \"help the New York police.\u201d It was a curious way of doing it.\nReader\u2019s\nComments\nTo the Editor:\nI prefer not to have\nname published in this connec\ntion, but I do want to compli\nment the TOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL and Mr. Duck for\nthose two fine articles on mu\nsic-in-industry. We have look\ned into the thing and contem\nplate establishing such a pro\ngram in our plant.\nmy\nIncidentally, for Mr. Duck\u2019s\nbenefit, The Library of Con\ngress recommends some excel\nlent sources of data on indus\ntrial music, including \u201cExperi\nments on the effects of music\non factory production,\u201d by\nWillard A. Kerr, (Applied Psy\nchology Monograph No. 5,\nJanuary, 1945, Stanford Uni\nversity Press, Palo Alto, Cali\nfornia), and \u201cMusic and sound\nsystems in industry,*\u2019 by Bar\nbara Elna Benson,, published\nby McGraw-Hill, New York\nCity.\nSincerely,\n(Name withheld by request)\nVeterans\ninformation\nQ\u2014Is the widow of a World\nWar I or a World War II vet\neran entitled to a pension\neven though the husband had\nno service-connected disabili\nty.\nA\u2014For World War I wid\nows the answer is yes. Bene\nfits are payable under Public\nLaw 483, 78th Congress, if the\nveterans* service meets the re\nquirements and the widow\u2019s\nincome does not exceed limita\ntions established by law. A\nWorld War II widow whose\nhusband had no service con\nnected disability is not eligible\nfor pension.\nto\nCommittee\nreputation\non\nof\nQ\u2014Is it true that National\nService Life Insurance pays\nthe 1 nsured veteran $5 per\nmonth for each 1,000 of in\nsurance in force while he is\ntotally disabled?\nA\u2014If the veter. i pay the\nnecessary extra p. c.nium, he\nwill be paid $5 per month for\neach $1,000 of insurance in\nforce after he has been totally\ndisabled for consecutive\nmonth Application for total\ndisability income may be\nmade at your local VA office.\nQ\u2014Can the beneficiary or\nfamily of a veteran make\npremium payments on his Na\ntional Service Life Insurance\nif the veteran doesn\u2019t care to\ndo so?\nA\u2014Yes, but the insured\nveteran has the right to\nchange his beneficiary or\nbeneficiaries at any time with\nout consul*!\"g with or receiv\ning the approval of anyone.\nHe may also surrender his\npermanent NSLI policy for\ncash at any time.\nQ\u2014I bo\u201d\"ht my hor-in with\nout a GI 1\" \u2019i. May I ..cure a\nguaranteed loan to buy furni\nture for it?\nA\u2014No.\nCongress Will Have\nVoice In Labor\u2019s\nPolitical Perspective\nBy Bradford L. Carter\nThe 81st Congress will be\nwatched by the men and wo\nmen of organized labor as few\nof its predecessors have been.\nLabor\u2019s organizations, the\ntrade unions and their politi\ncal action leagues, played\nmuch more of a dirtect role in\nits selection than workers have\nbefore.\nThey\u2019re going to keep their\neyes on specific bills\u2014for low\ncost housing, for improved so\ncial security, for health insur\nance, and for attacks upon in\nflation. They\u2019re demanding\nquick action to repeal Taft\nHartley, and they\u2019re concerned\ntoo about civil rights legisla\ntion and the development of\nour natural resources.\nLabor believes that in 1950\nit will be able to retire more\nreactionaries. And certainly it\nwill make short shrift of men\nelected with its support who\nfail to come through in sup\nport of labor\u2019s liberal legisla\ntive program.\nBut that\u2019s not the whole\nstory. More is at stake than\nthe fate of specific bills, and\nthe political fortunes of incum\nbent Congressmen. The Demo\ncratic 81st Congress will do\nmuch to determine the future\npolitical thinking and electoral\naction of the American labor\nmovement.\nMost unionists think that\nthe workers can best accomp\nlish their political goals by\nsupporting their friends and\nopposing their foes in both\nmajor parties. In most cases\nthis has meant supporting\nDemocrats.\nThe accomplishments of the\nNew Deal, strengthened the\nfeeling of the labor movement\nthat more is to be gained by\nbacking major party candid\nates than by supporting new\npolitical ventures.\nThis past election Henry\nWallace was rejected not only\nfor this reason, but because\nmost of labor recognized his\nparty as Communist inspired,\nand in some cases actually de\nsirous of defeating not reac\ntionaries but proven friends of\nthe workers.\nThere have always been\nhowever a few respected\npeople in the labor movement\nwho have said that labor must\norganize itself politically, just\nas it has economically. They\nhave maintained that despite\ntheir differences neither Dem\nocrats nor Republican politi\ncians can be trusted to \u201cde\nliver* on the campaign prom\nises they have made to labor.\nBut, by and large, these\nmen made relatively little\nheadway in \u201cselling\u201d their ap\nproach to most of their fellow\nunionists. One of the answers\nof the majority always has\nbeen that labor doesn\u2019t\nenough strength to go\npolitics directly and so\nsupport party nominees\nfavorable to its program.\nhave\ninto\nmust\nmost\nSince November, however, a\nnew synthesis is emerging be\ntween their attitude and that\nof the union men who have\nfavored vigorous labor politi\ncal action. It is that labor must\ncreate its own Independent\nmachinery, marshall its mem\nbers as voters, and keep up a\nconstant campaign to align un\norganized citizens in behalf of\nprogressive programs.\nAlthough encouraged to con\ntinue working with the major\nparties primarily the Demo\ncratic party\u2014as a result of the\n1948 experience, most union\nleaders feel that their political\nvehicles must\npendent, that\nunionists and\nshould be to\naction, not to any party. Their\nassumption is tnat they will\ncontinue to -work with 'and\nthrough the major parties, in\nbehalf of good candidates and\nplatforms.\nremain inde\nthe loyalty of\ntheir friends\nlabor political\nBut\u2014and this is where the\n81st Congress comes in\u2014if the\npeople labor helped elect to\noffice do not live up to the\npledges they\u2019ve made to the\nworkers, they\u2019re going to find\norganized labor taking more\nand more of a direct hand in\nthe spelling out of platforms\nand the selection of candidates.\nJoin th\nFIGHT\nMARCH\nOF\nDIMES\nINFANTILE\nPARALYSIS\nIHHV\u2019l- 'IU\n1H( MliOMAl lOmiHON FOR\ni.\n-x k\u00bb\nFriday, Deoethber SI, 1948\nRegional\nViews\nBy Richard Gosser\nVice-President\nInternational UAW-CIO\n\u201cThere is some curious\u2019\u2019 twist in the busi\nness mind which majces it suspicious of the\nright answer. Consider what happens to most\nproblems that are tossed into a conference.\nThe sound solution is most always simple and\nobvious. But the regular practice is to struggle\nall afternoon to find some compromise with\nthe right way. It seems to be accepted as evi\ndence of a shrewd business mind to be able\nso to confuse and muddy a proposition that\nno one ever will think straight about it again.\u201d\nTruer words were never spoken. Execu\ntives of management, labor and government\nshould reflect on this little motto, for sus\npicion of the right answer and the desire to\ndo things the complicated way have resulted in\na lot of needless trouble for all of us, not to\nmention the untold amount of time and money\nunnecessarily wasted.\nSome people say \u201cno\u201d to most everything.\nOthers kick a proposition so completely out\nof shape that even its author cannot recognize\nit in its final form. Why can\u2019t we do things\nthe easy, logical way? Must we hash, rehash,\nand debate every problem until it reaches the\nproportions of a federal case?\nWe are living in a fast moving world, one\nthat requires people to specialize, to know the\nanswers quickly and surely in his particular\nfield. The doctor cannot attempt to tell Mr.\nMooney how to build or sell his Jeepster, nor\ncan the barber tell the doctor how to diagnose\na case of diphtheria any more than either the\ndoctor or Mr. Mooney could tell the barber\nhow to cut hair.\nIn his very interesting book on labor\nmanagement relations and the functions of\nAmerican business \u201cOr Forfeit Freedom,\u201d\n(Doubleday, Garden City, N-Y Robert Wood!\nJohnson explains the simple, direct, and 3/\nobvious method by which good public rela\ntions can be obtained by American industry.\nHe says:\n\u201cAny plan that relies on employee co-,\noperation must be voluntary. Nothing can bo\ngained by drill, propaganda, or pep meetings\nwhat the worker does must and should be\nwilling, unregimented service. It will rest\nfirst of all on his own god relations his tl\nfeeling of satisfaction, his confidence in man\nagement, his pride in himself as a worker, and i\nas a worker with his company. He must feels*\nthat he works for one of the best companies\nin the country, with top management that is\nfair and decent, with likeable and reasonable\nforemen, with a top-notch working force, and\nand with reputable products. No company\nwhose employees fail to hold these opinions^\nand boast about them has even started to first\nbase in good public relations.\u201d\nRobert Wood Johnson is a specialist in\nhuman relations, and he knows more than a\nlittle about public relations. If anyone doubts\nthat he knows the answers, that person has\nonly to read his book to find\ndoes know them.\nEmployee good will goes hand in\nwith good labor relations. Management will\ndo well to cultivate a good working relation\nship with the union, fsom top to bottom,\nbuilt on a foundation of mutual trust and\nrespect. Grievances should be settled at the\ngrass roots level, not allowed to ffester and\nspread ill feeling.\nIn short, give the workers the things they\nwant and need. Accept the union don\u2019t try\nto fight it ,and it won\u2019t fight you. Above all,\nextend real security to your employees that\nway you\u2019ll attract the best available workers\nand keep them with you. Do this by in\naugurating a worthwhile pension plan and a\nreal insurance program.\nIf management cannot accept these sugges\ntions without a lot of ifs, buts, and strings\nattached, the only other suggestion I can offer\nis that the opening paragraph-of this column\nbe re-read.\nHappy New Year!\nWe, Too\nBy RUTH TAYLOR\nIt is a habit with the majority in speaking\nof the minority to comment on how careful\nthey ihust be, to say that, like Caesar\u2019s wife,\nthey must always be above reproach, that each\nand every act must be watched, and that the\nindividual must consider the effect of his\nactions upon the group from which he coipes.\nThat is plain horse sense\u2014I\u2019ve preached it\nmyself.\nBut sometimes I wonder if the majority in\nthis country ever realizes that this applies. It\nto us as well\u2014that we are but a minority in\nthe world, by both race and nationality.\nIt is up to us at all times to be good adver\ntisements for democracy and for the demo\ncratic way of life.\nWe preach to the Europeans of the folly\nof their national and trade barriers, or the\ndividing lines between countries. But we\ndon\u2019t see anything tragic, only humorous, in\nthe story of the Boston gentlewoman who\ncould not understand why there should be a\nfog in San Francisco when it was three thous\nand miles away from THE ocean.\nWe turn to the East and talk to the Asiatics\nof the wonders of Democracy and of how they\nshould conduct their lives. But how well do\nwe demonstrate the brotherhood of mankind?\nHow good is our own record? Both national\nand personal? Are we entirely guiltless?\nEvery act of discrimination, every out\nbreak of intolerance, every one of the vituper\native cat fights in which we indulge during\npolitical campaigns is a black mark against\ndemocracy in the eyes of the onlooking worlds\nOf course we know what we mean. We\ndiscount half our own talk. But the people\nof other nations take us at face value and ask:\n\u201cIs that democracy?\u201d\nhew well he\nworld intelli\npropagandists\nIn an enlightened economic\ngent management will replace\nwith human relations experts.'Good labor\nrelations ARE good public relations. Manage-\nment must be willing to accept the right\nanswers without suspicion. Good labor rela- tf\ntions come as the by-product of good human if\nrelations. Year-end bonuses to employees as, v\nwell as to executives go a long way toward^\ncreating genuine everyday employee interest\nin corporate welfare. Good will can be had\nquite easily by the promotion of nice recrea\ntional programs and a few extra concessions\nhere and there. One might suggest that\nagement give the workers the things\nonce gave them in an attempt to keep\nout of the union.\na\nman*\nthey\nthem\nhand\n0\n\u2022c\n1\n\u00a31","height":"27027","width":"19860"}}
